# Reference accessed: 2026-05-31 via gh api.
#
# hetzner-k3s is **the easiest way to create
# production-ready Kubernetes clusters on Hetzner
# Cloud** (3,574 GH stars at probe time).  Pivots
# from R298 lutra (Pony stdlib `cli`) into the
# **Crystal Admiral library cluster** — the
# **second Crystal CLI library variant** in the
# corpus after R269's stdlib `OptionParser`.
# **MAJOR MILESTONE**: expands the Crystal slot in
# the cross-language CLI taxonomy from 1 to 2
# variants — corpus now documents BOTH the stdlib
# (`OptionParser`) and the popular third-party
# (`Admiral`) Crystal CLI libraries.  Total library
# taxonomy: 38 variants.
#
# Critical extraction note: hetzner-k3s uses
# **Crystal `Admiral` library** at src/hetzner-k3s.
# cr:1 — jwaldrip/admiral.cr is the **most popular
# third-party Crystal CLI library** (sister tools
# also using Admiral: mint-lang/mint compiler,
# psykube, snipline/snipcli, jbox-web/stacker,
# djmaze/swm, refi64/rcmake, marghidanu/decompose).
# Distinct from Crystal stdlib `OptionParser` (R269
# zacchae/snek/various) which uses block-builder
# DSL.  Admiral uses CRYSTAL INHERITANCE + MACROS:
# a `class MyCLI < Admiral::Command` with
# `define_flag` and `register_sub_command` macros.
# Documents the **inheritance-plus-macro CLI
# pattern** — distinct from R269 OptionParser
# block-builder, R285 Lua argparse builder, R295
# CL clingon `make-option`, R296 Julia
# `@main`-on-function (no class).  Crystal Admiral's
# approach is similar to Java picocli's
# `@Command(subcommands = {...})` (R276) but
# substitutes ANNOTATION-CLASS DISCOVERY with
# CLASS-INHERITANCE + MACRO EXPANSION.  Corpus's
# **first documented inheritance-plus-macro CLI**.
#
# Critical extraction note: hetzner-k3s uses
# **NESTED INNER CLASSES for subcommand classes**
# at src/hetzner-k3s.cr:36/71/101/132/146 — each
# subcommand (Create, Delete, Upgrade, Releases,
# RunCmd) is defined as a NESTED INNER CLASS inside
# `Hetzner::K3s::CLI`.  Subcommand classes inherit
# from `Admiral::Command` (NOT from the outer CLI
# class).  Documents the **nested-inner-class
# subcommand pattern** — distinct from R294 Pharo
# pillar (separate top-level classes per
# subcommand) and R290 Racket `#:subcommands`
# (data list).  Crystal's nested classes share
# namespace with the outer class but inherit
# independently.  Corpus's **first documented
# nested-inner-class subcommand CLI pattern**.
#
# Critical extraction note: hetzner-k3s uses
# **`define_flag NAME : TYPE, description:, long:,
# short:, required:, default:` macro** at src/
# hetzner-k3s.cr:40/47/54/etc — `define_flag` is
# Admiral's CRYSTAL MACRO that EXPANDS at compile
# time to generate a typed flag-accessor method.
# Crystal macro syntax `NAME : TYPE` (capitalized
# colon-typed declaration) IS THE FLAG DECLARATION;
# the macro generates `flags.<name>` getter at
# compile time.  Documents the **macro-with-typed-
# declaration CLI pattern** — distinct from R294
# Pharo `addFlag: #templatable description: '...'`
# (runtime cascade), R295 CL clingon `:long-name
# "..."` keyword arg, R296 Julia `tune::Bool=false`
# function signature.  Crystal Admiral's macro
# parses the TYPED DECLARATION (`NAME : TYPE`) and
# generates appropriate parsing code for the type
# at compile time.  Plus the `required: true`
# keyword arg makes the macro emit a runtime check
# that fails-fast if the flag is missing.
#
# Critical extraction note: hetzner-k3s uses
# **`register_sub_command NAME : CLASS, description:
# "..."` macro for subcommand routing** at src/
# hetzner-k3s.cr:213-217 — five `register_sub_
# command` calls wire each subcommand class to a
# subcommand NAME with a description.  Documents
# the **register-sub-command-by-class-reference
# pattern** — distinct from R294 Pharo
# `pillarCommandsList do: [ ... addSubcommand: each
# ]` (auto-discovery via `allSubclasses`), R292
# Erlang pattern-match dispatch `main(["sub" | Argv]
# )`, and R296 Julia `@cast` (Comonicon cast macro
# for subcommands).  Crystal Admiral's approach is
# EXPLICIT REGISTRATION — the developer lists each
# subcommand by class reference.  Corpus's **first
# documented explicit-class-reference subcommand
# registration**.
#
# Critical extraction note: hetzner-k3s uses
# **leading-double-dashes-in-long-name quirk** at
# src/hetzner-k3s.cr:108 — `long: "--new-k3s-
# version"` has a LEADING `--` while OTHER `long:`
# specs in the same file use bare names (e.g.
# `long: "config"` at line 42, `long: "quiet"` at
# line 49, `long: "skip-current-ip-validation"` at
# line 56).  Admiral STRIPS leading dashes
# internally so both forms work, but the
# inconsistency is preserved verbatim in upstream
# source — likely a developer-side mistake (copy-
# paste from CLI usage example).  Documents the
# **source-direct preservation of upstream
# inconsistency** — important reminder that source-
# direct extraction MUST faithfully reflect the
# spec as written, INCLUDING quirks.  Corpus's
# **first documented Admiral leading-dashes quirk**.
#
# Critical extraction note: hetzner-k3s uses
# **runtime mutually-exclusive flag validation** in
# RunCmd at src/hetzner-k3s.cr:180-188 —
# `if command_provided && script_provided` /
# `unless command_provided || script_provided`
# enforces XOR semantics on `--command` and
# `--script` (exactly ONE must be provided).
# Documents the **runtime mutually-exclusive
# validation pattern** — joins the cluster of R252
# saya (clap builder manual mutex), R291 Lem CL
# `when (and tcp stdio)` (runtime mutex), R292
# emqtt Erlang `{undefined, undefined}` case
# (mutually-required XOR), R298 lutra Pony (no
# such validation, all flags optional).  FIVE
# rounds now showing runtime cross-flag validation
# patterns across SIX languages (Rust, CL,
# Erlang, Crystal, Lua); this is a CONVERGENT
# PATTERN ACROSS LANGUAGES where the upstream lib
# lacks declarative mutex support.
#
# Critical extraction note: hetzner-k3s uses
# **bottom-of-file `CLI.run` invocation** at src/
# hetzner-k3s.cr:232 — `Hetzner::K3s::CLI.run`
# kicks off the whole CLI dispatch.  Admiral's
# `Command.run` is a CLASS METHOD that:
#   1. Parses ARGV against the registered subcommand
#      tree
#   2. Selects the matching subcommand class
#   3. Instantiates that class
#   4. Calls the instance's `run` method
# Distinct from R297 Prolog `main() :- ...`
# predicate (Prolog tradition) and R296 Julia
# `@main` decorator (Comonicon wraps the function).
# Crystal Admiral's `.run` is a STATIC ENTRY POINT
# that handles dispatch — no separate `main`.
# Corpus's **first documented static-entry-point
# CLI dispatcher**.
#
# Hunt-skip notes: skipped `_mint` (already in
# corpus + blacklisted; refers to UNRELATED Swift
# Mint package manager at yonaskolb/Mint — name
# collision with mint-lang/mint Crystal compiler),
# `_decompose` (already in corpus + blacklisted;
# marghidanu/decompose docker-compose helper).
# Probed `psykube/psykube` (Kubernetes deployment
# helper, less well-known), `caravel-tool/caravel`
# (build pipeline, niche), `snipline/snipcli` (CLI
# snippet manager, smaller adoption), `jbox-web/
# stacker` (CloudFormation wrapper, less popular),
# `djmaze/swm` (S3 wrapper, niche), `creadone/dl`
# (download tool, generic name conflict), `refi64/
# rcmake` (CMake wrapper, abandoned).  Chose
# hetzner-k3s: 3,574-star real production tool,
# complete Admiral spec in one self-contained file
# with FIVE subcommands representing distinct
# Admiral patterns (define_flag/define_help/
# define_version/register_sub_command), runtime
# mutex validation in RunCmd, AND an upstream
# inconsistency (leading-dashes in long: at line
# 108) worth documenting source-direct.

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1

_arguments -C \
  '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[show hetzner-k3s help]' \
  '(-v --version)'{-v,--version}'[show hetzner-k3s version]' \
  '1: :->subcommand' \
  '*:: :->args' && ret=0

case $state in
  subcommand)
    # Five subcommands from register_sub_command
    # calls at src/hetzner-k3s.cr:213-217.
    local -a subcmds
    subcmds=(
      'create:create a cluster'
      'delete:delete a cluster'
      'upgrade:upgrade a cluster to a new version of k3s'
      'releases:list the available k3s releases'
      'run:run a command or script on all nodes in the cluster'
    )
    _describe -t commands 'hetzner-k3s subcommand' subcmds && ret=0
    ;;
  args)
    case $line[1] in
      create)
        # Create class at src/hetzner-k3s.cr:36-69:
        # --config -c (required), --quiet -q,
        # --skip-current-ip-validation.
        _arguments -s -S \
          '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[show create help]' \
          '(-c --config)'{-c,--config}'=[path of the YAML configuration file (REQUIRED)]:config file:_files -g "*.(yaml|yml)"' \
          '(-q --quiet)'{-q,--quiet}'[suppress the sponsor message]' \
          '--skip-current-ip-validation[skip validation that your current IP is in allowed SSH/API networks]' \
          && ret=0
        ;;
      delete)
        # Delete class at src/hetzner-k3s.cr:71-99:
        # --config -c (required), --force, --quiet -q.
        _arguments -s -S \
          '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[show delete help]' \
          '(-c --config)'{-c,--config}'=[path of the YAML configuration file (REQUIRED)]:config file:_files -g "*.(yaml|yml)"' \
          '--force[force deletion of the cluster without prompts]' \
          '(-q --quiet)'{-q,--quiet}'[suppress the sponsor message]' \
          && ret=0
        ;;
      upgrade)
        # Upgrade class at src/hetzner-k3s.cr:101-130:
        # --config -c (required), --new-k3s-version
        # (required), --force, --quiet -q.  Note
        # line 108 long: "--new-k3s-version" has
        # leading-dashes quirk.
        _arguments -s -S \
          '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[show upgrade help]' \
          '(-c --config)'{-c,--config}'=[path of the YAML configuration file (REQUIRED)]:config file:_files -g "*.(yaml|yml)"' \
          '--new-k3s-version=[new version of k3s to upgrade to (REQUIRED)]:version:' \
          '--force[force upgrade of the cluster without prompts]' \
          '(-q --quiet)'{-q,--quiet}'[suppress the sponsor message]' \
          && ret=0
        ;;
      releases)
        # Releases class at src/hetzner-k3s.cr:132-144:
        # no flags.
        _arguments -s -S \
          '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[show releases help]' \
          && ret=0
        ;;
      run)
        # RunCmd class at src/hetzner-k3s.cr:146-207:
        # --config -c (required), --command,
        # --script, --instance.  Note runtime XOR
        # validation on --command vs --script at
        # lines 180-188.
        _arguments -s -S \
          '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[show run help]' \
          '(-c --config)'{-c,--config}'=[path of the YAML configuration file (REQUIRED)]:config file:_files -g "*.(yaml|yml)"' \
          '(--script)--command=[command to execute on all nodes (mutex with --script via runtime check)]:command:' \
          '(--command)--script=[path to script file to execute on all nodes (mutex with --command via runtime check)]:script:_files' \
          '--instance=[instance name to run on (default: all instances)]:instance:' \
          && ret=0
        ;;
    esac
    ;;
esac

return ret
